additional_context.raw_instruction: deploy my project to Google Cloud, use docker compose

network_settings.ingress: Use Cloud Run domain mapping or HTTPS Load Balancer if later moving to GKE; for Cloud Run jobs/services from Compose, map service ports accordingly
network_settings.egress: Use default internet egress; add Serverless VPC Access connector if private resources are required later

infrastructure.container_orchestration: docker compose (locally) + Cloud Run (recommended target on GCP for Compose-like deployment)

deployment_strategy.summary: Containerize the app and deploy container services to Google Cloud Run using Docker Compose semantics where possible; use Cloud Build for image builds and optional Cloud Deploy or GitHub Actions for CI/CD.
deployment_strategy.rationale: GCP does not natively run docker-compose as a managed service. The closest managed, cost-effective target for containerized web/services without Kubernetes is Cloud Run. Compose can be used locally for orchestration and testing; each service is deployed as its own Cloud Run service. This meets the user's instruction to use Docker and Compose while deploying to Google Cloud.

actions: Identify actual app language(s) and entrypoints
List required environment variables and secrets
Determine exposed ports for each service
Catalog dependencies on databases, storage, and external services
steps.output: Minimal service matrix (service name, Dockerfile path, port, env vars, CPU/memory needs)

actions: Create a Dockerfile for each service with a minimal base image for the detected language
Add .dockerignore to reduce context size
Ensure the service listens on 0.0.0.0 and uses PORT env var if HTTP-based (Cloud Run requirement)
Build and run locally with docker compose up to verify
steps.output: Dockerfile(s), optional docker-compose.yml for local dev

actions: For each compose service, map to a Cloud Run service
Translate compose fields: image/build -> Cloud Build build config, ports -> Cloud Run container port, env -> Cloud Run env vars, resources -> Cloud Run CPU/memory
If you have multiple services communicating, use internal URLs or a VPC connector if needed
gcloud init and select/create GCP project
Enable APIs: run.googleapis.com, cloudbuild.googleapis.com, artifactregistry.googleapis.com
Create Artifact Registry repo (e.g., location us-central1, format Docker)
Grant Cloud Run, Cloud Build service accounts necessary roles (Artifact Registry Writer/Reader, Cloud Run Admin/Developer as appropriate)
steps.output: Enabled services and repos for builds

actions: Add cloudbuild.yaml with one image build per service (or use gcloud builds submit per service)
Push images to Artifact Registry: REGION-docker.pkg.dev/PROJECT/REPO/SERVICE:TAG
steps.output: Versioned container images in Artifact Registry

actions: gcloud run deploy SERVICE --image=... --region=... --platform=managed
Set env vars: --set-env-vars KEY=VALUE,...
Set resources and concurrency as needed (start conservative: 0.5–1 vCPU, 512Mi–1Gi)
If public HTTP: --allow-unauthenticated; otherwise configure IAM and private ingress
If multiple services: repeat per service; use service URLs for inter-service calls
steps.output: Cloud Run services per compose service

actions: Optionally map a custom domain via Cloud Run domain mapping
Add HTTPS load balancer only if you need a single entry point for multiple services or advanced routing
Configure Serverless VPC Access connector if private DBs or VPC-only resources are needed
Choose managed services: Cloud SQL, Memorystore, Firestore, Cloud Storage as required
Do not run persistent databases in Cloud Run containers; connect via private IP or IAM DB Auth Proxy
Store uploads in Cloud Storage, not container filesystem
Set up Cloud Build triggers from your repo (branch main) to build and deploy on push
Alternatively use GitHub Actions with gcloud auth and gcloud run deploy
Tag images with commit SHA; use substitutions for environments
Rely on Cloud Run autoscaling (min instances 0 by default; set min if cold-start sensitive)
Use Cloud Logging and Cloud Monitoring dashboards/alerts
Set request concurrency and max instances according to performance tests

notes: Your inputs do not confirm existing Dockerfile or compose files; these must be created.
Scaling and HA are unspecified; Cloud Run provides autoscaling and multi-zone redundancy by default in a region.

If you truly need docker-compose in production as-is, consider running it on a managed VM (Compute Engine) or a single-node GCE with Docker installed; however, this shifts ops burden to you. GCP does not provide a native compose service.
If you later need more complex service-to-service networking or stateful sets, consider GKE with Compose-to-Kubernetes tools (kompose) or Helm.
quick_commands: gcloud services enable run.googleapis.com cloudbuild.googleapis.com artifactregistry.googleapis.com
